  "title": "_pydecimal Standard Library Module in Python 3.12+",
  "summary": "This explainer provides an overview of the _pydecimal standard library module introduced in Python 3.12, focusing on its purpose, key features, and examples.",

  "key_points": [
    "_pydecimal is a backward-compatible replacement for the deprecated decimal module.",
    "It provides high precision arithmetic with guaranteed correct rounding according to IEEE 754 Rounding Modes.",
    "The _PyDecimal class can represent numbers of arbitrary precision and maintain precision during calculations.",
    "_pydecimal also offers support for context managers, allowing users to specify the desired rounding mode."
  ],

  "code_examples": [
    {
      "language": "python",
      "code": "from _pydecimal import Decimal\n\n# Instantiate a _PyDecimal object with high precision.\nnum1 = Decimal('12345678901234567890')\n\n# Perform arithmetic operations on _PyDecimal objects.\nnum2 = num1 + Decimal('9876543210987654321')\nprint(num2)"
    },
    {
      "language": "python",
      "code": "from _pydecimal import getcontext\n\n# Set the context for rounding mode.\ngetcontext().rounding = ROUND_HALF_DOWN\n\n# Perform arithmetic operation within the specified context.\nnum1 = Decimal('0.5') + Decimal('0.1')\nprint(num1)"
    }
  ],

  "version_notes": [
    "_pydecimal is available in Python 3.12 and later.",
    "The _PyDecimal class replaces the Decimal class from previous versions."
  ],

  "caveats": [
    "While _pydecimal provides high precision arithmetic, it may lead to slower performance compared to standard float operations due to the increased memory requirements of arbitrary-precision numbers."
  ]
